To export checkbox values from an HTML table to an Excel file using the xlsx.js library, you will need to traverse the table, retrieve the checkbox values, and generate an Excel file using xlsx.js. Here's an example implementation:

1. Include the xlsx.js library in your HTML file:
```html
<script src="https://unpkg.com/xlsx/dist/xlsx.full.min.js"></script>
```

2. Create an HTML table with checkboxes:
```html
<table id="myTable">
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Item</th>
      <th>Checkbox</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Item 1</td>
      <td><input type="checkbox" checked></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Item 2</td>
      <td><input type="checkbox"></td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Item 3</td>
      <td><input type="checkbox" checked></td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<button onclick="exportToExcel()">Export to Excel</button>
```

3. Use JavaScript to export the checkboxes to an Excel file:
```javascript
function exportToExcel() {
  // Initialize empty workbook
  var wb = XLSX.utils.book_new();

  // Get table element
  var tbl = document.getElementById("myTable");

  // Create worksheet
  var ws = XLSX.utils.table_to_sheet(tbl, {sheet: "Checkbox Data"});

  // Process the checkboxes
  var rows = ws['!rows'];
  for(var r = 1; r < rows.length; r++) {
    var isChecked = tbl.rows[r].cells[1].querySelector("input[type=checkbox]").checked;
    ws['B' + (r + 1)].v = isChecked ? 'Checked' : 'Not checked';
  }

  // Add worksheet to workbook
  XLSX.utils.book_append_sheet(wb, ws, "Checkbox Data");

  // Save workbook as Excel file
  var today = new Date();
  var fileName = "checkbox_data_" + today.getFullYear() + "-" + (today.getMonth() + 1) + "-" + today.getDate() + ".xlsx";
  XLSX.writeFile(wb, fileName);
}
```

When you click the "Export to Excel" button, the checkbox values from the table will be exported to an Excel file with the name `checkbox_data_currentDate.xlsx`.

Note: Make sure to include the xlsx.js library in the proper location and update the table and button IDs as necessary.

